statement:
Consider the differential equation system

\begin{align*}\mathbf{y}'=A\mathbf{y}\end{align*}

where A has eigenvalues $\lambda_1=-1$ and $\lambda_2=-2$ with
corresponding eigenvectors

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{k}_1=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2
\end{bmatrix},\qquad
\mathbf{k}_2=
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

What is the general solution of the system of differential equations?

sols:
Recall that a solution to

\begin{align*}\mathbf{y}'=A\mathbf{y}\end{align*}

with eigenvalues $\lambda_1$, $\lambda_2$ and eigenvectors
$\mathbf{k}_1,\mathbf{k}_2$ is

\begin{align*}\mathbf{y}(t)=c_1\mathbf{k}_1\exp(\lambda_1{t})+c_2\mathbf{k}_2\exp(\lambda_2{t}).\end{align*}

Therefore, for this specific example, the solution is,

\begin{align*}\mathbf{y}(t)=c_1
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2
\end{bmatrix}\exp(-t)
+ c_2
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix}\exp(-2t).\end{align*}
